  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much tax do a non resident earning 60000$/annum have to pay in USA?",
  "response": "Taxation for non-residents in the United States can be complex and depends on various factors such as the type of income, source of income, tax treaties, and other considerations. Generally, non-residents are subject to U.S. taxes on U.S.-sourced income.\n\nHere are some general points to consider:\n\n1. **Non-Resident Alien Tax Status**: Non-residents are usually subject to withholding taxes on U.S.-source income at flat rates of 30%, unless a tax treaty specifies a lower rate.\n\n2. **Types of Income**:\n    - Income effectively connected with a U.S. trade or business (ECI) is taxed at graduated rates similar to U.S. residents. This may include employment income, business profits, etc.\n    - Fixed or determinable annual or periodic (FDAP) income, such as interest, dividends, rents, royalties, etc., are subject to 30% withholding tax unless reduced by a tax treaty.\n\n3. **Tax Treaties**: Some countries have tax treaties with the U.S. which may provide reduced tax rates or exemptions on certain types of income, potentially affecting the taxation of your $60,000 annual income.\n\nFor a non-resident alien who has income effectively connected with a U.S. business, the federal income tax rates for 2023 are progressive. The first $11,000 is typically taxed at 10%, the next portion up to $44,725 is taxed at 12%, the next up to $95,375 at 22%, and so forth. The specific tax liability would depend on allowable deductions and potentially applicable tax treaties.\n\nHere\u2019s a rough estimate of the federal tax liability for a non-resident alien earning $60,000 as effectively connected income:\n\n1. Up to $11,000 at 10% = $1,100\n2. From $11,001 to $44,725 at 12% = $4,047\n3. From $44,726 to $60,000 at 22% = $3,347.28\n\nTotal federal income tax = $1,100 + $4,047 + $3,347.28 = $8,494.28\n\nAgain, this is a simplified calculation and actual taxes owed may vary based on specific circumstances, deductions, credits, and any applicable tax treaties.\n\nIt's recommended to consult with a tax professional or use IRS resources to get an accurate assessment based on your unique situation.",
